# GitHub Repo Standards - Environment Configuration Example
#
# This file shows all available configuration options for the compliance scanner.
# Copy these to GitHub repository variables/secrets as needed.
#
# Location: Repository Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions
#
# ============================================================================
# REQUIRED SECRETS
# ============================================================================
# These MUST be configured as Repository Secrets for the scanner to work.
# Get these values from your GitHub Apps (see SETUP.md for creation guide).

# Repo Standards Bot - App ID
# Location: Organization Settings → GitHub Apps → [Your App] → About → App ID
REPO_STANDARDS_APP_ID=123456

# Repo Standards Bot - Private Key
# Location: Organization Settings → GitHub Apps → [Your App] → Generate a private key
# Format: Full PEM format including header/footer
# -----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----
# ...
# -----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----
REPO_STANDARDS_APP_PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\n...\n-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----"

# Internal Automation App - App ID
# Location: Organization Settings → GitHub Apps → [Your App] → About → App ID
INTERNAL_AUTOMATION_APP_ID=123457

# Internal Automation App - Private Key
# Location: Organization Settings → GitHub Apps → [Your App] → Generate a private key
# Format: Full PEM format including header/footer
INTERNAL_AUTOMATION_APP_PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\n...\n-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----"

# ============================================================================
# OPTIONAL VARIABLES
# ============================================================================
# These can be configured as Repository Variables to customize behavior.
# If not set, sensible defaults (shown below) are used automatically.

# Name of the repository containing the compliance framework
# Default: github-repo-standards
# Change if: You've renamed this repository
STANDARDS_REPO_NAME=github-repo-standards

# Maximum number of parallel compliance check jobs
# Default: 10
# Increase: For faster scans (if not hitting rate limits)
# Decrease: If hitting GitHub API rate limits
MAX_PARALLEL_JOBS=10

# Number of days to retain compliance check artifacts
# Default: 30
# Increase: For longer audit trails
# Decrease: To save storage space
ARTIFACT_RETENTION_DAYS=30

# Default branch name for automated PRs
# Default: main
# Change if: Your organization uses a different default branch
DEFAULT_BRANCH=main

# Label applied to compliance issues in target repositories
# Default: compliance
# Change if: You want different label names for your organization
COMPLIANCE_LABEL=compliance

# Label applied to critical compliance issues
# Default: critical
# Change if: You want different label names for your organization
CRITICAL_LABEL=critical

# ============================================================================
# SETUP INSTRUCTIONS
# ============================================================================
#
# 1. Create GitHub Apps:
#    - See docs/setup.md → "GitHub Apps Setup" section
#    - Create both Repo Standards Bot and Internal Automation apps
#    - Note the App IDs and download private keys
#
# 2. Configure Repository Secrets:
#    - Go to: Repository Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions → Secrets
#    - Click "New repository secret"
#    - Add all 4 required secrets (APP_ID and PRIVATE_KEY for each app)
#
# 3. Configure Repository Variables (Optional):
#    - Go to: Repository Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions → Variables
#    - Click "New repository variable"
#    - Add any variables you want to customize (defaults work for most cases)
#
# 4. Verify Configuration:
#    - Go to: Actions tab
#    - Run workflow: Repository Compliance Check (Matrix)
#    - Check for errors in workflow logs
#
# ============================================================================
# SECURITY NOTES
# ============================================================================
#
# - NEVER commit this file with actual values to git
# - Private keys are sensitive - treat them like passwords
# - Use GitHub Secrets (not Variables) for all sensitive data
# - Review API_PERMISSIONS.md for detailed permissions explanation
# - See SECURITY.md for additional security considerations
#
# ============================================================================
